The whole project is a single-handed non-stop round the world yacht race. In order to study its potential influence among all the parameters, it is divided into three parts: first we collect all the necessary data from website. And a pre-processing work is dones in the second part. Finally, we analysed the obtained dataset from different aspects and draw a conclusion in the end.¶

1. Acquisition et chargement des données¶

In this part, we will fisrtly collect all the excel files from the website using beautifulsoup and urllib library. Secondly, we will scrap the website to get a technical file about boat's information for each skipper.¶

a. Récupération des fichiers Excel avec les classements¶

# from the website classement, download historical rank Excel file  
def get_classement_list(url):
    classement_list = []
    res = requests.get(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(res.content,'html.parser')
    dates = soup.find_all('option')
    names = dates[1:]
    # choose how many files we want 
    for t in names:
        name = t.get('value')
        name_classement = f'vendeeglobe_{name}.xlsx'
        link = f'https://www.vendeeglobe.org/download-race-data/vendeeglobe_{name}.xlsx'
        try:
            download_url(link)
            classement_list.append(name_classement)
        except OSError as e:
            print(name, "error")
    return classement_list

# obtain technique dataframe from the websit 'Glossaire' by using BeautifulSoup 
def get_fiche_technique(url):
    res = requests.get(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(res.content,'html.parser')
    fichier_tech = soup.find_all('div', class_ = "sv-u-1 sv-u-s-1-2 sv-u-m-1-3 sv-u-l-1-6")
    df = pd.DataFrame()
    data = []
    for t in fichier_tech:
        l = []
        a = [] 
        skipper = t.find('span', class_='boats-list__skipper-name').text
        boat = t.find('h3', class_='boats-list__boat-name').text
        l = [skipper, boat]
        boat_info = t.find('ul', class_='boats-list__popup-specs-list').text.strip().split('\n')
        a = ['None']*14
        ref = ['Numéro de voile',
         'Anciens noms du bateau',
         'Architecte',
         'Chantier',
         'Date de lancement',
         'Longueur',
         'Largeur',
         "Tirant d'eau",
         'Déplacement (poids)',
         'Nombre de dérives',
         'Hauteur mât',
         'Voile quille',
         'Surface de voiles au près',
         'Surface de voiles au portant']
        for i in range(len(boat_info)):
            name = boat_info[i].split(': ')[0].strip()
            variable = boat_info[i].split(': ')[1]
            ind = ref.index(name)
            a[ind] = variable
        l = l + a
        data.append(l)
    
    name = ['Skipper', 'Bateau'] + ref
    df = pd.DataFrame(data, columns = name)        
    return df

# fonction to convert latitude and longitude
def convert(tude):
    deg = int(tude.split('°')[0])
    mn = float(tude.split('°')[1].split("'")[0])
    if tude[-1] in ['N', 'E']:
        multiplier = 1
    else:
        multiplier = -1
    return multiplier * (deg + mn / 60)

# pre-processing on Excel dataframe
def traitement_excel(filename):
    df = pd.read_excel(filename, header=[3,4]).iloc[0:32,1:]
    col_name = (('Rang', ''),
            ('Nat. / Voile', ''),
            ('Skipper / Bateau', ''),
            ('Heure FR', ''),
            ('Latitude', ''),
            ('Longitude', ''),
            ('Depuis 30 minutes', 'Cap'),
            ('Depuis 30 minutes', 'Vitesse / kts'),
            ('Depuis 30 minutes', 'VMG / kts'),
            ('Depuis 30 minutes', 'Distance / nm'),
            ('Depuis le dernier classement', 'Cap'),
            ('Depuis le dernier classement', 'Vitesse / kts'),
            ('Depuis le dernier classement', 'VMG / kts'),
            ('Depuis le dernier classement', 'Distance / nm'),
            ('Depuis 24 heures', 'Cap'),
            ('Depuis 24 heures', 'Vitesse / kts'),
            ('Depuis 24 heures', 'VMG / kts'),
            ('Depuis 24 heures', 'Distance / nm'),
            ('DTF / nm', ''),
            ('DTL / nm', ''))
    df.columns = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples(col_name)
    # remove units for speed, distance etc
    df['Latitude'] = df['Latitude'].apply(lambda x: convert(x))
    df['Longitude'] = df['Longitude'].apply(lambda x: convert(x))
    a = [x for x in range(6, df.shape[1])]
    l = [3] + a
    for i in l:
             df.iloc[:, i] = df.iloc[:, i].apply(lambda x: x.split(' ')[0])
             df.iloc[:, i] = df.iloc[:, i].apply(lambda x: x.split('°')[0])
    # create four new columns which sperate variables nation, voile, skipper and bateau
    df.insert(2, 'Nation', df['Nat. / Voile'].apply(lambda x: x.split(' ')[0].split('\n')[1]))
    df.insert(3, 'Voile', df['Nat. / Voile'].apply(lambda x: x.split(' ')[1]))
    df.insert(5, 'Skipper', df['Skipper / Bateau'].apply(lambda x: x.split('\n')[0]))
    df.insert(6, 'Bateau', df['Skipper / Bateau'].apply(lambda x: x.split('\n')[1]))
    # convert numerical varibale to numeric type
    a = [x for x in range(10, df.shape[1])]
    l = [0, 3] + a
    for i in l:
             df.iloc[:, i] = pd.to_numeric(df.iloc[:, i])
    # convert and complete Heure FR with datetime 
    da = filename.split('/')[-1].split('_')[1]
    df['date'] = f'{da[0:4]}-{da[4:6]}-{da[6:]}'
    df['Heure FR'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date']+' '+df['Heure FR'])
    # change data type for other variables:
    l = [2, 5, 6]
    for i in l:
             df.iloc[:, i] = df.iloc[:, i].astype(str)
    df['Skipper'] = df['Skipper'].apply(lambda x: x.capitalize())
    df = df.drop(df.loc[df['Skipper']== 'Nicolas troussel'].index)

    return df

# Pre-processing on data of technic file
def traitement_fiche_tech(df):
    pd.options.mode.chained_assignment = None
    # replace comma to dot 
    df = df.apply(lambda x: x.str.replace(',', '.'))
    # convert date de lancement to datetime type
    df['Date de lancement'] = df['Date de lancement'].apply(lambda x: dateparser.parse(x).date())
    df['Date de lancement'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date de lancement'])
    # convert variable to numerical type
    l = [7, 8, 9, 12, 14, 15]
    for i in l:
        df.iloc[:, i] = df.iloc[:, i].apply(lambda x: x.split('m')[0])
        df.iloc[:, i] = pd.to_numeric(df.iloc[:, i])
    df.iloc[:, 10] = df.iloc[:, 10].apply(lambda x: x.split('t')[0])
    # uniform 'skipper' format
    df['Skipper'] = df['Skipper'].apply(lambda x: x.capitalize())
    # since 'Nicolas Troussel' didn't participate in contest, we remove him 
    df = df.drop(df.loc[df['Skipper']== 'Nicolas troussel'].index)
    # some irregular Skipper name
    df['Skipper'][df.loc[df['Skipper']=='Sam davies'].index] = 'Samantha davies'
    df['Skipper'][df.loc[df['Skipper']=='Alan  roura'].index] = 'Alan roura'
    df['Skipper'][df.loc[df['Skipper']=='Arnaud boissières'].index] = 'Arnaud boissieres'
    # change df to multiIndex in order to be coherent with fiche classement
    df.columns = pd.MultiIndex.from_product([df.columns, ['']])
    return df

# merge two dataframes on 'Skipper' name
def merge_voile_classement(fiche_tech, fiche_classement):
    df_merge = pd.DataFrame()
    df1 = fiche_tech.copy()
    df2 = fiche_classement.copy()
    df_merge = pd.merge(df2, df1, how='left', on='Skipper')
    return df_merge

# fonction to combine the files
# df: historical rank files with technic file
# classement_ensemble: only historical rank files
def ensemble_classement(classement_list, df_technique):
    df = pd.DataFrame()
    classement_ensemble = pd.DataFrame()
    for name in classement_list:
        df_merge = pd.DataFrame()
        filename=f'/Users/delin/Desktop/final_projet/{name}'
        df_classement = traitement_excel(filename)
        df_merge = merge_voile_classement(df_technique, df_classement)
        df = df.append(df_merge)
        classement_ensemble = classement_ensemble.append(df_classement)
    return df, classement_ensemble

3. Analyses des données¶

In this part, we will discuss six questions: relation between rank and VMG, influence of existance foil to VMG and rank, visualization of traveled distance and map of skipper, an analysis in time series and finally we use Lasso algorithm to find out the most important features for skipper's rank.¶

1. Corrélation et régression linéaire entre le classement (rang) et la vitesse utile (VMG) des voiliers.¶

a. From one single rank Excel file¶

In [50]:

In [51]:
# study correlation between rank and VMG
corr_30m = rang.corr(VMG_30m, method='pearson')
corr_dernier = rang.corr(VMG_dernier, method='pearson')
corr_24h = rang.corr(VMG_24h, method='pearson')
print('Pearson’s r Value Correlation Between rang and VMG depuis 30 minutes est', round(corr_30m,2),
     '\nPearson’s r Value Correlation Between rang and VMG depuis le dernier classement est', round(corr_dernier,2),
     '\nPearson’s r Value Correlation Between rang and VMG depuis 24 heures est', round(corr_24h,2))

Pearson’s r Value Correlation Between rang and VMG depuis 30 minutes est -0.11 
Pearson’s r Value Correlation Between rang and VMG depuis le dernier classement est -0.32 
Pearson’s r Value Correlation Between rang and VMG depuis 24 heures est -0.18

We know that the Pearson correlation coefficient can take on any real value in the range −1 ≤ r ≤ 1. The maximum value r = 1 corresponds to the case when there’s a perfect positive linear relationship between x and y. And the minimal value r = −1 corresponds to the case when there’s a perfect negative linear relationship between x and y.

In our case, the value r < 0 indicates negative correlation between x and y, which means that rank and VMG have a negative correlation. Bigger the value of rank is, smaller the value of VMG is. It is logical with our common sense: a skipper with big VMG will have a small value in his rank (better rank) and vice versa. Moreover, absolute value of correlation coefficient for VMG since 30 minutes and VMG since 24 hours are smaller than VMG since the last rank, which indicates that VMG since last rank is a better representation of a skipper.

From the graph, we saw that globally VMG and rank have a negative relation which is coherent with correlation coefficients. Moreover, VMG since last rank gives the best performance where points are less dispersed around the linear regression curve.

We say that VMG since last rank is a best criterion to decide the rank of each skipper, because VMG since 30 minutes or since 24h may vary based on skipper's strategy. However, VMG since last rank is relatively stable and gives us an average performance of each skipper, it can be a representation of a skipper's performance.

In [63]:
# find 'DISTANCE À L'ARRIVÉE' from the website
url = 'https://www.vendeeglobe.org/fr/classement'
res = requests.get(url)
soup = BeautifulSoup(res.content,'html.parser')
fichier_tech = soup.find_all('div', class_ = "rankings__item")
time = soup.find('p', class_ = "rankings__subtitle").text
data = []
Dis = []
Bat = []
for t in fichier_tech[:-1]:
    l = []
    total_dis = 45000
    skipper = t.find('p', class_="rankings__desc").text
    name = skipper.strip().split('                      ')[0]
    bateau = skipper.strip().split('                      ')[1]
    rank = t.find('li', class_="rankings__stats").text
    distance = float(rank.strip().split('\n')[2].split(' ')[0])
    distance = round((total_dis - distance),1)
    l = [name, bateau, distance]
    Dis.append(distance)
    Bat.append(bateau)
    data.append(l)

# visualisation of skipper's path by using ipyplet library

m = Map(center = (0, -17), zoom=2)
colors_list = list(colors._colors_full_map.values())

    # put latitude and logitude in a list as couple
    loc = []
    skipper_name = N[i]
    a = route.loc[route['Skipper']==skipper_name]['Latitude']
    b = route.loc[route['Skipper']==skipper_name]['Longitude']

        loc.append(l)

# visualization of skipper's rank in time series
def plot_rank_time(choose_name):
    plt.figure(1,figsize=(15,10))
    rank_time = classement_ensemble[classement_ensemble['Skipper']==choose_name]['Rang'].values.tolist()
    size = classement_ensemble[classement_ensemble['Skipper']==choose_name]['Rang'].size
    x_name = [i for i in range(size)]
    time_stamp = classement_ensemble[classement_ensemble['Skipper']==choose_name]['Heure FR'].astype(str).tolist()
    plt.plot(x_name, rank_time,label=choose_name)
    l=[i*(size//5) for i in range(5)]
    time_stamp = [time_stamp[i] for i in l]
    plt.xticks(l, time_stamp)
    plt.xlabel('')
    plt.ylabel('rank')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title(f'Evolution of rank for skipper [{choose_name}], from {time_stamp[0]} to {time_stamp[-1]}', fontsize=14);

6. Application d'algorithmes de machine learning pour prédire le rang¶

In this section, we want to use Lasso linear regression algorithm to select the most important features for the rank. Moreover, we want to see the prediction accuracy obtained by different features.¶

In [56]:
# This function allows us to convert str to numeric
def to_numeric(df, cols):
    le = LabelEncoder()
    df_copy=df.copy()
    for col in cols:
        df_copy[col] = le.fit_transform(df_copy[col].astype('str'))
    return df_copy
In [60]:
# applt function to_numeric to change cols dtypes 
cols = ['Nation', 'Déplacement (poids)', 'Nombre de dérives', 'Voile quille', 'Skipper', 'Heure FR','Date de lancement']
df_num = to_numeric(df, cols)

At the beginning, we study the importance of each feature to rank,so we make rank as our target so y and other columns as the features so X. However, some features have the same nature like 'Voile','Numero de voile', and some features don't relate to rank like 'Anciens noms du bateau', so we remove these 'useless' columns from our X.

In [61]:
# preparation of dataframe X_total which contains nearly all the features in df
cols_drop = ['Nat. / Voile', 'date','Skipper / Bateau', 'Bateau_x', 'Bateau_y',
             'Numéro de voile', 'Anciens noms du bateau', 'Architecte','Chantier', 'Rang']
X_total = df_num.drop(cols_drop, axis=1)
y = df_num[['Rang']].values
X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test = train_test_split(X_total, y, test_size=0.2,random_state=42)
In [62]:
# choose the optimal regularisation parameter for Lasso
lassocv = LassoCV(cv=5)
lassocv.fit(X_train, y_train.ravel())
print("The optimal regularisation parameter for Lasso is", round(lassocv.alpha_, 3))

# Lasso estimator
lasso = Lasso(alpha=lassocv.alpha_)
lasso.fit(X_train, y_train)
print("R2 score of Lasso is", round(r2_score(y_test, lasso.predict(X_test)), 3))

# feature selected by Lasso: coefficients is not null
lasso_var = np.where(lasso.coef_ != 0)[0]
print(f"Features selected by Lasso are:", X_total.columns[lasso_var])

# visualization of the results
plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
plt.plot(lasso.predict(X_test), label='pred')
plt.plot(y_test, label='real')
plt.xlabel('samples')
plt.ylabel('estimated rank')
plt.legend()
plt.title('All features: Rank estimated by Lasso')
plt.legend();

Knowing that best possible R2 score is 1.0, so closer R2 score to 1.0, better our estimator is. In our case, we obtained an estimator with R2=0.712 which is a relative good estimator. Moreover, thanks to the characteristics of Lasso estimator, il allows exsitence of null coefficients for some features, so that we can find more meaningful features to predict rank. Here we found Voile, Cap since last rank,Cap since 30m, Released Date, Traveled distance since 24 hours, DTL(the distance to the end), DTF(the distance to first skipper) and surface of the voile are the most important features to rank.

Moreover, we want to study if the structure of the boat will influence the results of competition. So now we will use purely the features provided by df_technique to see their relationship.

# choose the optimal regularisation parameter for Lasso
lassocv = LassoCV(cv=5)
lassocv.fit(X_train, y_train.ravel())
print("The optimal regularisation parameter for Lasso is", round(lassocv.alpha_, 3))

# Lasso estimator
lasso = Lasso(alpha=lassocv.alpha_)
lasso.fit(X_train, y_train)
print("R2 score of Lasso is", round(r2_score(y_test, lasso.predict(X_test)), 3))

# feature selected by Lasso: coefficients is not null
lasso_var = np.where(lasso.coef_ != 0)[0]
print(f"Features selected by Lasso are:", X.columns[lasso_var])
